metaData.descriptionCS:
For both the picture and verbal items,
the child mentally solves arithmetic
problems within a specified time limit.

questions.title: †Item 1. Dogs
questions.incorrectInstructionsHTML:
†Incorrect response:

Say, There are three dogs. Point to each dog from the child’s left to right as you count them aloud at the rate of about one per second.
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Point to the child’s screen and say, Count these dogs with your finger. Count them out loud.

questions.title: †Item 2. Chicks
questions.incorrectInstructionsHTML:
†Incorrect response:

Say, There are five chicks. Point to each chick from the child’s left to right as you count aloud at the rate of about one per second.
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Point to the child’s screen and say, Count these chicks with your finger. Count them out loud.

questions.title: †Item 3. Trees
questions.incorrectInstructionsHTML:
†Incorrect response:

Say, There are ten trees. Point to each tree from the child’s left to right as you count aloud at the rate of about one per second.
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Point to the child’s screen and say, Count these trees with your finger. Count them out loud.

questions.title: Item 4. Butterflies
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Point to the child’s screen and say, How many butterflies (point to butterflies) and grasshoppers (point to grasshoppers) are there all together?

questions.title: Item 5. Squirrels
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Point to the child’s screen and say, How many nuts (point to nuts) will be left if each squirrel (point to squirrels) eats one?

questions.title: Item 6. Books
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Remove the Client Device from the child’s view before proceeding to the verbal items.

Ann has 6 books. She loses 1. How many books does she have left?

questions.title: Item 7. Apples
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Pam has 5 apples. She gives 1 to Rob and 1 to Jill. How many apples does Pam have left?

questions.title: Item 8. Toys
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Neal has 2 toys. He gets 3 more. How many toys does he have all together?

questions.title: Item 9. Blocks
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Sam has 4 blocks. His mom gives him 3 more. How many blocks does he have all together?

questions.title: Item 10. Grapes
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Ruth has 3 grapes in each hand. How many grapes does she have all together?

questions.title: Item 11. Friends
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Zach has 12 friends and makes 3 more. How many friends does he have all together?

questions.title: Item 12. Dolls
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Jean has 8 dolls and gets 6 more. How many dolls does she have all together?

questions.title: Item 13. Balloons
questions.topInstructionsHTML: George has 11 balloons and loses 3. How many balloons does he have left?

questions.title: Item 14. Games
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Jack played 10 games on Monday and 15 games on Tuesday. How many games did he play all together?

questions.title: Item 15. Frogs
questions.topInstructionsHTML: There are 3 frogs in a pond. Then, 4 more frogs jump into the pond, and 2 frogs jump out. How many frogs are left in the pond?

questions.title: Item 16. Birds
questions.topInstructionsHTML: There are 8 birds on the ground. Then, 4 birds fly away, and 2 other birds land. How many birds are on the ground now?

questions.title: Item 17. Tickets
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Tom has 12 tickets and his teacher gives him 2 more. He sells 5. How many tickets does he have now?

questions.title: Item 18. Crayons
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Rick has one hundred crayons. He gives each of his 2 brothers 40 crayons. How many crayons does he have left?

questions.title: Item 19. Lights
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Kate counted 17 lights on a street and 15 on another street. How many lights did she count all together?

questions.title: Item 20. Songs
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
To introduce Items 20–34, say, I am going to read you some more problems. This time, you can ask me to read each problem one more time.

Each item may be repeated at the child’s request one time only, but do not alter the wording in any way. If the child requests a repetition, immediately pause timing and repeat the item. Resume timing after the last word of the repeated item, and continue timing until the child responds or the time limit expires.

Belle has 30 minutes of free time, but spends half of it cleaning her room. If playing 1 song takes 5 minutes, how many songs can she play in the free time she has left?

questions.title: Item 21. Track
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Each child runs in only 1 race at a track meet that has 8 races. If 3 children run in each race, how many children are in the track meet all together?

questions.title: Item 22. Soccer
questions.topInstructionsHTML: A soccer team has 30 children. After a week, 11 children leave the team, and 2 new children join. How many children are on the team now?

questions.title: Item 23. Rings
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Rose gives 3 of her friends 2 rings each and gives another friend 7 rings. How many rings does she have left if she started with 20 rings?

questions.title: Item 24. Classrooms
questions.topInstructionsHTML: A school has 25 students in each classroom. If there are 500 students in the whole school, how many classrooms are there?

questions.title: Item 25. Pieces
questions.topInstructionsHTML: On Monday, Jane spends 3 hours working on a puzzle. On Tuesday, she finishes it after working 2 more hours. The puzzle has 300 pieces. On average, how many pieces did she finish each hour?

questions.title: Item 26. Cakes
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Ron makes 12 cakes between 4 AM and 8 AM. He makes 9 cakes between 8 AM and 11 AM. On average, how many cakes does he make each hour?

questions.title: Item 27. Comics
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Beth has two-thirds as many comic books as Ray. Beth has 20 comic books. How many comic books does Ray have?

questions.title: Item 28. Children
questions.topInstructionsHTML: There are 71 children on a bus. At the first stop, 17 get off. At the next stop, 11 get off, and at the last stop, 32 get off. How many children are left on the bus?

questions.title: Item 29. Papers
questions.topInstructionsHTML: A student wrote 13 papers. Another student wrote 11 papers. Then, 25 other students wrote 5 papers each, and 2 more students wrote 1 paper each. How many papers did the students write all together?

questions.title: Item 30. Cars
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Six people can wash 40 cars in 4 days. How many people would it take to wash 40 cars in half of a day?

questions.title: *Item 31. Boys
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Out of 40 children, 15% of them are girls. How many children are boys?

*If the child says “85%,” say, Yes, but how many boys is that? Do not stop timing to provide this query.

questions.title: Item 32. Seeds
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Wes starts planting seeds 1 hour before Val does. Wes plants 40 seeds each hour and Val plants 60 seeds each hour. How many more seeds has Val planted than Wes 5 hours after Wes starts planting?

questions.title: Item 33. Exercise
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Nick exercises every Saturday by swimming, bike riding, and jogging. First, he swims for 25 minutes, stretches for 10 minutes, and then swims again for 45 minutes. After a 5 minute break, he rides his bike uphill for 20 minutes, on flat land for 45 minutes, and downhill for 15 minutes. After another 5 minute break, he jogs for one hundred and twenty minutes and sprints for 10 minutes. If Nick starts exercising at 6:30, what time is it when he finishes?

questions.title: Item 34. Levels
questions.topInstructionsHTML: A game has 20 levels. Lee must score 300 points to pass each level, and she must pass a level before going to the next one. If Lee scores one thousand five hundred points per hour, and she plays without stopping for 2 hours and 15 minutes, how many levels will she have left to play?

consecutiveZerosDiscontinueRule.description: Subtest requires 3 consecutive scores of 0 points
